abcd:Representation.abcd:Title: TalTech geological collections
abcd:Representation.abcd:Details: Geological and paleontological collections housed at the Institute of Geology at Tallinn University of Technology (formerly an institute of the Estonian Academy of Sciences) are the largest of their kind in Estonia. The particular strength of the collection lies in Ordovician and Silurian invertebrates and Devonian fish fossils of the Baltica paleocontinent. Most of the ca 300000 specimens are collected since the mid 20th century, few collections date back to 1850s.
abcd:Representation.abcd:Coverage: Invertebrate and early vertebrate fossils, and sedimentary rocks primarily from the Paleozoic strata of Baltic Region and former Soviet Union; Quaternary sediments and fossils from Estonia; minerals and meteorites of worldwide coverage.

abcd:TermsOfUse.abcd:Text: Free for non-commercial usage, provided that Department of Geology at TalTech and https://geocollections.info are acknowledged.

abcd:Disclaimer.abcd:Text: We make efforts to ensure that the data we serve are accurate. However, quality and completeness of every data record cannot be guaranteed. Use the data at your own responsibility.

abcd:Acknowledgement.abcd:Text: National geological collection of Estonia; Department of Geology, TalTech

abcd:Citation.abcd:Text: National geological collection of Estonia; Department of Geology, TalTech

abcd:Gathering.abcd:LocalityText: Museum of Art excavation section, Kadriorg

abcd:UnitReference.abcd:CitationDetail: Database of global glendonite and ikaite records throughout the Phanerozoic
